-- Gold Fields, Illovo, Northam, SasolMay Move: South African Equity Preview
-- Franz Wild
-- 2010-07-21T05:51:11Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-07-21/gold-fields-illovo-northam-sasolmay-move-south-african-equity-preview.html

          
          
             The following is a list of companies
whose shares may have unusual price changes in  South Africa .
Stock symbols are in parentheses after company names and prices
are from the last close.  
 South Africa’s  FTSE/JSE Africa All Share Index  rose for a
third time in four days, advancing 19.86, or 0.1 percent, to
27,349.61 at the close in Johannesburg.  
 Gold Fields Ltd.  (GFI SJ): A mineworker was killed in an
accident at Gold Fields’s Driefontein mine, the National Union
of Mineworkers said in an e-mailed statement. The stock of Gold
Fields, Africa’s second-largest producer of the metal, was
unchanged at 96 rand.  
 Illovo Sugar Ltd.  (ILV SJ): Africa’s biggest producer of
the sweetener holds its annual general meeting. Illovo’s stock
rose 17 cents, or 0.6 percent, to 29.27 rand.  
 Kumba Iron Ore Ltd.  (KIO SJ): The Anglo American Plc unit
in March asked South African Mineral Resources Minister  Susan Shabangu  not to grant prospecting rights for the Sishen mine in
the Northern Cape to Imperial Crown Trading because of mining-
law contraventions, Business Day reported today. Kumba rose 3.90
rand, or 1.1 percent, to 347.90 rand.  
 Northam Platinum Ltd.  (NHM SJ): The operator of the deepest
mine producing the metal said two workers were killed in an
accident at its Zondereinde mine, according to a stock exchange
statement. Northam’s stock fell 35 cents, or 0.8 percent, to
43.60 rand.  
 Randgold & Exploration Co.  (RNG SJ): The gold producer said
earnings in the first half through June will rise as much as
11.05 rand per share. The stock was unchanged at 5.40 rand.  
 Sasol Ltd.  (SOL SJ): The world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal said its fertilizer settlement agreement with
South Africa’s competition authorities “will not have a
material adverse financial impact” on the company, according to
a stock exchange filing. Sasol’s stock rose 20 cents, or 0.1
percent, to 280.40 rand.  
 Simmer & Jack Mines Ltd.  (SIM SJ): The gold-mining company
said the Department of Mineral Resources transferred the mining
rights for the Tau Lekoa mine to its Buffelsfontein Gold Mines
Ltd. unit from AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. Simmers advanced 3 cents,
or 3.8 percent, to 82 cents.  
 Shares or American depositary receipts of the following
South African companies closed as follows:  
 Anglo American Plc (AAUKY US) gained 1.6 percent to $18.27.
AngloGold Ashanti Ltd. (AU US) jumped 1.1 percent to $39.53. BHP
Billiton Plc (BBL US) added 4.7 percent to $57.92. DRDGold Ltd.
(DROOY US) rose 1.2 percent to $4.10. Gold Fields Ltd. (GFI US)
increased 1.8 percent to $12.72. Harmony Gold Mining Co. (HMY
US) dropped 0.9 percent to $9.94. Impala Platinum Holdings
(IMPUY US) advanced 2.1 percent to $24.56. Sappi Ltd. (SPP US)
added 1.9 percent to $4.38. Sasol Ltd. (SSL US) rose 1.4 percent
to $37.10.  
